Pyroscope: Monolith → Microservices Mode on OpenShift
Platform Engineering Guide · Diataxis Format · Vert.x Java Agent Edition
Audience: Platform Engineers owning the observability stack on OpenShift
Scope: Pyroscope monolith (single-binary) → full microservices decomposition, capacity
planning, and team communication artifacts
Stack: OpenShift 4.x, Pyroscope 1.x, Vert.x reactive Java agent (async-profiler), S3-compatible
object store
Table of Contents
1. Explanation — Understanding Pyroscope Architecture
2. How-To — Migration Runbook
3. Reference — Ports, Hardware, Policies, Config
4. Tutorial — End-to-End Lab Walk-Through
5. Capacity Planning — Sizing Tables & Models
6. Diagrams — Mermaid Architecture & Flow
1. Explanation
Mode Description When to Use
Monolith All components in one process, local disk storage Dev, PoC, single-node
VM
Microservices Each component is an independent, horizontally-
scalable Deployment
Production, HA, multi-
tenant
1.1 Why Two Deployment Modes Exist
Pyroscope (Grafana-maintained continuous profiling backend) ships as a single binary that can be
run in two modes:
In your current state you are running monolith mode on a VM with Vert.x apps pushing profiles via
the Java agent. This works fine until you need: HA, horizontal scale, tenant isolation, or GitOps-
managed OpenShift deployments.
1.2 The Pyroscope Read / Write Path
Understanding the path is critical for capacity planning and network policy design.
Write Path (Ingestion):
Java Agent (async-profiler)
└─ HTTP POST /ingest (push) or Pyroscope pull scrape
└─ Distributor ← stateless, receives profiles
└─ Ingester ← in-memory ring buffer (WAL)
└─ Object Store (S3/MinIO/GCS) ← parquet + index blocks
Read Path (Query):
Grafana / Pyroscope UI
└─ Query Frontend ← request fan-out, caching
└─ Querier ← fetches from store-gateway + ingesters
├─ Store Gateway ← index + block reads from object store
└─ Ingester ← in-flight data not yet flushed
1.3 Why Vert.x Reactive Architecture Needs Special Attention
Vert.x uses a non-blocking event-loop model (Netty under the hood). This creates two profiling
challenges:
1. CPU profiling: Async-profiler’s ITIMER signal works correctly on event-loop threads. However,
wall-clock profiling ( event=wall ) is preferred for reactive workloads because ITIMER misses
blocked-but-waiting coroutines.
2. Thread naming: Vert.x creates threads named vert.x-eventloop-thread-N . The Java agent
must be configured to capture these by pattern, not just by default thread groups.
Agent config recommendation for Vert.x (push mode):
-javaagent:/opt/pyroscope/pyroscope.jar
-Dpyroscope.application.name=my-vertx-service
-Dpyroscope.server.address=http://pyroscope-distributor:4040
-Dpyroscope.profiler.event=wall
-Dpyroscope.profiler.alloc=512k
-Dpyroscope.profiler.lock=10ms
-Dpyroscope.upload.interval=15s
-Dpyroscope.labels=env=prod,region=us-east,vertx=true
Key: profiler.event=wall captures event-loop idle/waiting time, which is the dominant latency
source in reactive systems. profiler.event=cpu would miss it.
