6.7 Capacity Decision Tree
flowchart TD
A([Start: How many\nVert.x pods?]) --> B{≤ 20 pods?}
B -- Yes --> C[Small Tier\n2 dist, 3 ing, 2 QF\n2 nodes 8c/32Gi]
B -- No --> D{≤ 100 pods?}
D -- Yes --> E[Medium Tier\n2 dist, 3 ing, 2 QF\n3 nodes 16c/64Gi]
D -- No --> F{≤ 500 pods?}
F -- Yes --> G[Large Tier\n3 dist, 6 ing, 2 QF/QR\n5 nodes 32c/128Gi]
F -- No --> H[XL Tier\nHPA + dedicated node pool\nEngage Grafana for Mimir migration]
C --> I{Multi-tenant?}
E --> I
G --> I
I -- Yes --> J[Add X-Scope-OrgID\nEnable tenant isolation\nPer-tenant limits config]
I -- No --> K[Single-tenant\nNo token header needed]
J --> L([Deploy + Monitor\npyroscope_ingester_active_series\npyroscope_distributor_received_bytes
K --> L
Appendix A — Team Communication One-Pager
Copy this block for Slack/Confluence/Jira to brief app teams.
Subject: Pyroscope Profiling Endpoint Migration — Action Required
We are migrating the continuous profiling backend (Pyroscope) from a VM to OpenShift
microservices. Your Vert.x service needs one configuration change.
What changes:
Before After
http://pyroscope-
http://pyroscope-distributor.observability-
vm.internal:4040
pyroscope.svc.cluster.local:4040
What does NOT change: your JVM flags, profiler settings, or application code.
When: Cutover week of [DATE]. You will receive a Helm values update or env patch to your
Deployment.
Impact if not updated: Profiles will continue to flow to the old VM for up to 7 days after cutover,
then stop. No application behavior is affected — profiling is out-of-band.
Who to contact: #platform-observability Slack channel.
